'''Eilif Hvide Bang''' (15 April 1892 – 28 January 1953) was a Norwegian businessperson.

He was born in [[Oslo|Kristiania]] as a son of consul-general Thomas Cathinco Bang (1863—1929) and Louise Bielke. In 1923 he married Edda Louise Albertovna Schoeneckerl from [[St. Petersburg]].<ref name=hvem48>{{cite encyclopedia|year=1948|title=Bang, Eilif|encyclopedia=[[Hvem er hvem?]]|editor=Steenstrup, Bjørn|publisher=Aschehoug|location=Oslo|url=http://runeberg.org/hvemerhvem/1948/0036.html|page=36|language=Norwegian|accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref>

He [[examen artium|finished]] his secondary education in 1910, took business education in [[Köln]] and [[Dresden]], Germany from 1910 to 1912 and worked in Germany, England, France and Sweden from 1912 to 1916. He was hired as office manager at [[Södra Cell Tofte|Tofte Cellulosefabrik]] in 1916, and was promoted to manager in 1927 and chief executive officer in 1929.<ref name=hvem48/><ref name=merkbio>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Bang, Eilif|url=http://runeberg.org/merkbio/0396.html|encyclopedia=[[Merkantilt biografisk leksikon]]|publisher=Yrkesforlaget|location=Oslo|edition=1st|editor-last=Hoffstad|editor-first=Einar|editor-link=Einar Hoffstad|year=1935|page=318|accessdate=8 May 2012|language=Norwegian}}</ref>

He served as president of the [[Federation of Norwegian Industries (1919–1989)|Federation of Norwegian Industries]] from 1947 to 1950.<ref>{{cite news|title=Industriforbundets nye president|date=24 April 1947|work=[[Aftenposten]]|page=1|language=Norwegian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Statsråd Evensen liker heller ikke dirigering|date=28 April 1950|work=[[Aftenposten Aften]]|page=1|language=Norwegian}}</ref> He also chaired the French-Norwegian Chamber of Commerce from 1937, was a board member of [[Oslo Sparebank]], deputy board member of the [[Norwegian Industrial Bank]] and supervisory council member of [[Forsikringsselskapet Norge]], the [[Norwegian America Line]] (deputy)<ref name=hvem48/><ref name=merkbio/> and Oslo [[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative Party]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Årsmøte i Oslo Høyres representantskap|date=14 March 1953|work=[[Aftenposten]]|page=5|language=Norwegian}}</ref> He was also a council member of ''[[Studieselskapet for Norsk Industri]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=Studieselskapet for Norsk Industri|date=25 November 1946|work=[[Aftenposten]]|page=10|language=Norwegian}}</ref> and ''[[Bygg ditt Land]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bygg Ditt Land har hatt et rikt virkeår|date=31 March 1952|work=[[Aftenposten]]|page=2|language=Norwegian}}</ref>

He was decorated as a Chevalier of the [[Légion d'honneur]].<ref name=hvem48/> He died suddenly in January 1953.<ref>{{cite news|title=Direktør Eilif Bang død|date=28 January 1953|work=[[Aftenposten Aften]]|page=2|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Marshals at his funeral were Gunnar Holst and Johannes Westergaard.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bisettelser|date=5 February 1953|work=[[Aftenposten Aften]]|page=4|language=Norwegian}}</ref>

