{{Use British English|date=February 2016}} {{Infobox officeholder |honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]] |name = Dame Pamela Gordon |honorific-suffix = DBE |image = |office1 = 6th [[Premier of Bermuda]] |term_start1 = 27 March 1997 |term_end1 = 10 November 1998 |monarch1 = [[Elizabeth II]] |governor1 = [[Governor of Bermuda#List of Governors of Bermuda|Thorold Masefield]] |2blankname1 = {{nowrap|Governor}} |2namedata1 = |deputy1 = |predecessor1 = [[David Saul]] |successor1 = [[Jennifer M. Smith]] |birth_date = September 1955 |birth_place = Bermuda |spouse = |children = |alma_mater = |party = [[United Bermuda Party]] }}
'''Dame Pamela F. Gordon''', [[DBE]] (born 1955) is a Bermudian politician who served as [[Premier of Bermuda]] from March 1997 until November 1998.
==Early life and education== Gordon was born in 1955, the daughter of [[Edgar F. Gordon]], a civil rights activist and labour leader who died six months before her birth and Mildred Layne Bean.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bermudasun.bm/Content/NEWS/News/Article/Mother-of-our-first-female-Premier-dies-at-88/24/270/66923|title=Mother of our first female Premier dies at 88|author=|date=|work=bermudasun.bm|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> Gordon was the youngest of five children born to her father and mother. Gordon became pregnant at 16 which meant she was forced to leave the private school she attended.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Pamela_Gordon.aspx|title=Pamela Gordon|author=|date=|work=encyclopedia.com|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> She subsequently attended [[Alma College (St. Thomas, Ontario)|Alma College]] in Ontario, Canada. She married the father of her daughter and had another child. However, her marriage ended in divorce. She is now married to Andrew Banks.
==Career== Prior to entering politics, Gordon managed a restaurant. Gordon was appointed to the [[Bermuda Senate]] in 1990 representing the [[United Bermuda Party]]. The centre-right United Bermuda Party is the main opponent of the centre-left [[Progressive Labour Party (Bermuda)|Progressive Labour Party]] founded by the political associates of her father. Gordon served as cabinet minister for Youth Development, Sports and Recreation between 1992-95. She was elected as a Member of Parliament in 1993, representing Southampton West and became Minister for the Environment, Planning, and Natural Resources, 1995. In 1997 Gordon became leader of UBP and the Premier of Bermuda. She was the youngest Premier and the first female Premier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unfoundation.org/features/cwwl-bios/current-cwwl-members/Pamela-Gordon.html?referrer=https://www.google.com.au/|title=United Nations Foundation - Pamela Gordon-Banks: Premier, Bermuda, 1997-1998|author=|date=|work=United Nations Foundation|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>
==After office== Gordon has been active in a number of organisations and campaigns concerning gender equality. Gordon also works with the Montpelier Foundation. She also serves on the Queen’s School of Business Global Council.
==Honours== Gordon has been honoured as a Dame Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire by Queen Elizabeth. In 2013 Gordon received an honorary degree from Queen's University in Canada<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queensu.ca/gazette/content/honorary-degree-recipients-straddle-science-politics|title=Honorary degree recipients straddle science, politics|author=|date=|work=queensu.ca|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> In December 2015 Gordon was honoured at a gala in New York celebrating female empowerment hosted by the Girl Be Heard theatre company. The company praised Gordon, saying "Dame Pamela Gordon-Banks has broken countless ceilings, educationally and economically. She thinks globally and acts locally".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalgazette.com/article/20151203/NEWS/151209870|title=Dame Pamela Gordon-Banks honoured at gala|author=|date=3 December 2015|work=The Royal Gazette|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>
